segments.text: A couple of things about the court trip that I want to reflect on.
You know, I'm trying to remember whether it was Rice or some other place.
That freshman court trip to Houston, I assume it was Rice, because I don't even know if it was Rice.
On Friday, we all went in three cars.
But there's quite some sisters in this.
This is about 35 people.
And then there was some people from .
And it was, I'll forever not know where it was.
But it was somewhere out in the 1960s, Humboldt area.
uh, house out in the family woods that this wife's sister and young husband lived in.
And all of a sudden, 30, 50, 40 city head cadets showed up with him.

And it was, you know, I'll never forget it, because I can't imagine how anyone, and these were just a young couple, probably not much older than his age, who found a way to feed all of us and put us all down and we slept in their house.
And it was the next night after, the real story I want to share is, during the, at halftime, the majorette for Rice came off the field
and grabbed the saber of the OD.
And the stands, within three to five seconds, emptied.
I've never seen, it was like a mass of humanity simply moving out of the stands.
And then, of course, the police, and then there were a few strategic blows struck, but it didn't last long.
But it was just, I will always remember how, there was no order given, there was no,
you know, someone organized, it just empty onto the field.
And of course, the second deck was trying to get down.
But everybody on the first deck, which was mostly students, went out there and tried to get a licking.
So there was always a little bit now, one other thing we haven't talked about Haskell is that the freshman class in the fall of 1963 was and will be forever
the mascot stealing champions of the Southwest Conference.
Oh, yes.
Please do describe it.
We had a young fellow who was a freshman over in one of the Air Force outfits whose name shall not be revealed, and a sophomore who was also sort of a ringleader who had planned all this out.
And we had a lousy football team in a pretty lousy school when you think about it.
So we had to do some things to distinguish ourselves.
And so they set about to capture every mascot in the Southwest Conference.
The distinguishing ones I remember is the one when they stole the horn frog
Ended up, the Horned Frog died.
I mean, this is, you know, there was one on every street corner in Fort Worth.
It wasn't like this was an endangered species in those days, but this was a big deal.
That was one thing.
Then, of course, the final blow was when they stole Bevo.
And, I mean, this, you think about it, this is quite a, quite a feat.
How could anybody steal UT's mascot?
I mean, I can't even imagine.
But anyway, they do.
And they have the mascot here.
And it's pastured on some territory supposedly owned by J.E.
Lupo.
And they gather us all in Guyon Hall.
And there's a big Texas Ranger with a hog leg on his side making a speech.
And one of the ending remarks is, boys, I just want to remind you, we still hang horse thieves in Texas.
And I want the damn steer back, and I want it back now.
I mean, this was a big deal.
And I think Rutter and Dean Hannigan, who was the dean of students, we were all petrified of, were on the stage.
And sure enough, they negotiated.
And I think it was probably because Lupo figured he was in trouble.
But they did negotiate finally sometime before the game started Bevo to be handed back to the proper authorities.
It was quite an occasion.
Is this the year they got one of the Baylor Bears and on the way back the Bear tore up the car?
They had tranquilized the Bear.

And apparently, while they were hauling, and it was just a Cub, it wasn't really a full, but on the way back, the tranquilizer wore off, and they had to exit the car, and the bear just tore the hell out of the inside of that car.
I mean, there were a lot of stories like that.
The SMU, they had a little miniature pony, and I don't remember what it was that happened to the pony, but they had to get a veterinarian involved.
And you know, when you think about it, you had a few faculty members around here that were probably in the know on some of that going on, too.
But I believe they stole every mascot that year.
Now, as far as you were aware, was it the same guys doing?
Yeah.
I mean, I'm sure all those guys must have flunked out of school after the fall semester because they could not have been going to class.
They were spending full time planning and executing the kidnappings.
Oh, another popular fellow on the campus at that time was the old bulldog named Ranger.
We called him Rutter because obviously he was owned by President Rutter's family and we would paint the predicted score on the old bulldog's side and then we would paint the real score and I'm
believe to this day he probably died of lead poisoning from all the paint that had been put on him.
But he had some peculiar habits.
One of the things he would do is he would roam the campus and he would walk out in front of your car if you were driving and wouldn't move.
And then if, you know, the only thing you could do was let him in the car, drive around the campus for a little while, and then let him out and he was fine.
But it was his way of getting a free ride and having some fun.
One night, and this was, I don't know what year, but I came back to my dorm room late, opened my door, and I heard something snoring very loudly.
And I flicked the light on and there was Rutter in my bed.
Some friends, quote, friends, had given him a place to sleep for the night.
So, you know, you just find another place to sleep and don't bother him anymore.
Where would you have found him?
Where's that other place?
Oh, just in another, somebody else's bed that was out of town.
Oh, okay.
I don't even remember.
Let's see, a general question.
It just pops in my brain.
In your four years as an undergraduate, do you remember anybody in the core area ever having any problems about theft?
No.
You know, I don't even remember locking my door.
That's what I thought.
And your car?
No, never.
You know, it just didn't happen.
Now, we had, as I said a while ago, we had some strange characters and sort of...
I figure it probably went like this.
The judge said Army, Marines, Texas A&M, or penitentiary.
And they ended up here as an alternative to those other places.
I don't know that for a fact, but I mean some of the people that we had were of that ilk.
But they weren't thieves, and they were just strange characters.
Some of them you would probably remember.
Some of them are very successful business people today.
Rod Dockery would be a name that comes to mind.
passionate would be an understatement.
He was a cruel, sadistic, mean individual.
I don't think he's that way today, but that's the way, and who knows how he got that way.
But you cut a wide swath around Rod Dockery if you saw him on the campus.
And I mean, I kind of like the guy today.
As you look back, you end up being corps commander and one of the true student leaders of that time.
During your freshman year, how did you begin to get headed in that direction?
Were there some people, some events, some organizations?
Well, you know, I don't know.
I mean, I'm not sure I can, I can't, I don't think it's one of those things that's predestined, and I don't think you, I don't really think you think about it.
I mean, frankly, my goal in life was to be company commander.
I mean, that was, to me, that was the sort of pinnacle job.
It's where you could make the most difference in terms of dealing with the kind of things we dealt with.
What happened, though, was, you know, a lot of what you, in those days, it was built around a couple of things.
One, you had to have the grades, which were, you know, I mean, they weren't the easiest thing in the world.
The second thing is you had to be reasonably proficient at the military stuff, uniform and drill and all of that.
And then you know whatever other ways you exhibited leadership, people had to identify and pick up on.
We didn't think about it so much as because we were watching ourselves.
We didn't realize other people were watching us too.
But do you realize now that you caught some people's attention as a freshman?
No, probably not.
I mean I was best drill or best freshman cadet or some sort of thing.
You were?
Yeah.
Okay.
In my outfit.
You know, and then you compete for that.
But most of that's doing right face, left face, and whether your shoes are shining and all that kind of stuff.
It doesn't have a lot to do with your leadership.
And then as you go through the ranks, people start beginning to recognize, for example,
And you know this story, I think.
I was first sergeant of my outfit my junior year.
To be corps commander, that's a strange route.
In fact, it's only happened one other time that I know of, and that was year before last.
But what's the part of that that's untold is this, that I interviewed for corps staff, and the process was, as a junior on corps staff, you were basically selected by the seniors

then you had to be verified by the commandant's office and all the the trigon bureaucracy but what had happened was we had a grade-wise we had a very poor class i was the only one in my outfit that had the grades to be first sergeant we the class ahead of us was worse than us we had no one who had the grades to be company commander
So they were going to import a person from another outfit to be company commander.
So I said, hey, I can't abandon the outfit.
We're going to end up with two people imported, the CO and the first sergeant.
That's not going to work.
So I basically decided to opt out of the competition for being a junior on staff to be the first sergeant in the outfit, which fundamentally was in keeping with my
targeted objectives anyway.
But what happened out of all that is I got exposed to some people who could see, you know, who I was.

And then the couple of fellows that were on first brigade staff and corps staff as seniors the year ahead of me began to observe some behavior and stuff as a first sergeant that said, hey, this guy might be okay.
And then in the senior year,
you get put into the system to be considered.
And then it was a long sort of crucible you went through to end up being selected.
Were the selection process interviews

started with cadets and then you ended up with all the military types including the commandant at that time a fellow named denzel baker dean hannigan the dean of student life or whatever dean of students and then the final interview was rutter but that one basically the the the interview with rutter was for him to just check off
By that time, you'd been scrubbed so many different ways that it would be very rare for him to say no.
In all of those interviews, that review process, in hindsight, what were the key talents, the key areas that they were concerned about?
Well, I think there were two or three things.
One is we had had a fellow the year before
as corps commander who was, I didn't really know him that well, but he was the son of an Air Force officer.
He was very, and don't forget now, we're in the Vietnam era.
He was very military, but not very, his leadership qualities weren't all that great, and he tended to be very aloof.
there were a lot of what I would consider to be sort of cultural negative issues in the Corps at the time.
I mean, the people at the bottom were not paying attention to the people at the top.
And I think one of the things that they were looking for is someone who could relate to the cadets up and down the line.
Another thing was we had a...
We were split in our living between the Duncan and Sbiza areas.
We had a lot of conflict in the Sbiza area with the civilian students.
These were kids that either started in the corps, and also remember this is transitioning from required corps to non-compulsory corps.
And then we had a lot of people that were coming in in those latter years straight into the institution with no experience in the corps.

And there was a lot of jealousy and, you know, not, I mean, it wasn't a revolution or anything, but there were just fundamental things like getting up in the morning and banging on the trash cans as you marched to chow so you'd wake up all the damn non-regs.
You know, I mean, so it was a, and they were looking for someone who could try to manage through this environment we had, which was converting from
compulsory corps, all military, had been very active in a lot of things that had corps and civilian students involved in it.
Student government, ag activities, the journalism program, which was primarily civilians.
There weren't very many corps.
Anyway, so I mean a lot of those things probably factored in.
Who knows?
I mean, I don't know.

why they made the decision as you look back do you remember because you obviously knew that you were being you were one of the candidates yeah is there any time when you felt hey that was a key that this was a key step um
No.
Reflecting back on it, you didn't get an air for action report.
Nobody told you why you were selected.
There were a couple of other things I would point out.
We had about three or four people in the ROTC program that were young captains and majors.
that were just out of Vietnam, typically, and these guys were sharp, they'd survived the experience, they had an eye for somebody they thought could exhibit leadership.
One of those, interestingly, was a fellow named Charlie Zip, who was one of the more interesting characters I've ever known.
It was rumored
that Zip had married somebody rich.
I don't know if that was true or not.
I mean, I know Margaret Ann now.
I don't know her well.
And Zip was also the only guy in the ROTC that had ever had saber drill.
So he was the one that taught us how to do saber drill.
And he'd been to West Point, so he was the big dog.
But he was an immensely funny, dry-witted guy
was influential, and then a couple of these young captains who were just fire eaters that were influential, I think, in the decision making.
Did anybody coach you about the interviews or anything?
No, never even, was never even thought about.
Did you turn to anybody for advice, did you?
No.
Right, how did you know,
When did you how and when did you learn the unfortunate thing is you just had to be honest Yeah, you know you said yeah, they ask you questions.
You told them what you thought right or wrong You know it's because there wasn't any there was no school for Going through this the interesting by the way.
I told you it was something interesting my freshman fish camp buddy Barney fudge was the sergeant major of the Corps and
So he would have been the heir apparent to be corps commander.
That was always the route.
Whoever was sergeant major the junior year typically was corps commander.
So when I was selected corps commander, you know, you then chose your own staff, again, with final approval, check off by the commandant.
But I asked Barney to be the core adjutant, which he accepted.
And we still remained fast friends, which if he were the kind of guy that would have been sort of inwardly thinking or egotistical, he would have said, go to hell.
I'm going to go do something else.
But he didn't do it.
That was your fish hole lady?
No, he was my, I met him at Fish Camp.
Remember, he was with Burke Burnett, Texas, and we became friends at Fish Camp, and then ended up being on staff together.
Now, in those days, remember, we're transitioning out of all corps.

We had Barney, who was the president of the student body, or in those days we called it president of the student senate, and sort of by virtue of that was the nominal president of the student body, the head Yale leader.
the head of the Ross Volunteers, one and the same, also the head stack who built the Bonfire, the president of the MSC, the editor of the Agriculturalist, the editor of the battalion.
Tommy got canned, so he wasn't there.
Well, I mean, we had all of the leadership positions basically embedded in corps staff.
So, you know, from a student perspective, you know, we were really well integrated in terms of all of the overall leadership.
How were you informed that you had been selected as corps commander?
This is an interesting story.
That spring, my junior year, among other courses I was taking was a very difficult course called Animal Reproduction.

and one of the uh requirements in animal reproduction was a weekly lab and one of the things that we learned to do in that weekly lab was to palpate cows to determine if they were pregnant and how far along and i probably very hard on the tape to explain the process but

needless to say it involves putting one of your upper appendages in the rear end of a cow and i had been in this lab for three hours with my uniform with what comes out of the rear end of a cow placed in unsightly places i get back to my dorm room uh late in the afternoon and on my you know on the door there were
You always had your name and your class schedule and all that.
Well, stuck up there was a note saying, come to the Commandant's office immediately.
Well, I mean, I didn't know for sure what it was, but I, you know, I was far enough along to have a pretty good idea.
But I don't have a clean uniform.
So I scramble around, and I find a uniform, but my shoes are covered in cow dung.
So my junior old lady was a guy named Mac who wore size 13 shoes.
So I borrowed Mac's shoes, sort of stuffed some stuff down in the toe, and hobbled my way across campus, showed up at Colonel Baker's office,

walked in and saluted feeling a little strange and he told me I'd been selected but I had a couple more uh well no no no that was after the rudder interview so I was anointed about what time of the year was this um I would say it was probably April
It was late in the year.
Now they make the selections very early.
But then it was probably within a month of the end of school.
All right, how did your life change then, between then and the next fall, beginning of the fall semester?
The first symptom was that I was, I had, and you'll love this Haskell, I put off taking History 105 and 106.
I don't know why, but I just did.
And so I was taking History 105 my second semester junior year.
I think I had Alan Ashcraft, I can't remember, but I had a good prof. And I went into the corps commander selection with a high A.
I finished that semester with a low C because I don't think I ever went back to class.
And all I did was just take whatever exams I had to take without doing any reading, without taking any notes, and just, you know, kind of bombed it.
So it was, it became a time of intense time commitment in terms of, you know, number one,
it would have been a little easier for someone who was already on core staff, who sort of was, knew all of the issues and techniques and people.
But I had to not only learn that, but I moved into an office in Dorm 2, which was the headquarters of the Corps at the time.
Slept on a box spring and mattress on the floor for that last month or so, just to get over and get broken in.
It was intense.
Then that summer, you go to camp?
Went to Army ROTC camp.
Joe Bush, who was selected the outstanding cadet who was Class 66, but in the summer camp in that summer of 66, later killed in the operation into Laos, as you may recall.
Joe Bush was in the outfit next to me.
One thing I do remember most about summer camp was we had a TAC officer who was out of a little school in Missouri, and I can't remember the name of it.
But he was a very poised and really good guy.
But he picked me out the first day and said, we've got to have somebody to lead the parade.
Now, he probably knew of my selection down here, but, I mean, you know, this was a little different.
This is cadets from all over the western United States.
And where are you?
Fort Sill.
Fort Sill.
Which, another thing.
Not very far away from home.
Not very far from home.
In fact, we made a deal, and I got the word out to all the junior cadets I could find,

telling them if they'd like to stop off in henrietta at the farm on the way up it was sort of like fish whites experience we had probably 40 kids spend the night with us on the way to and my dad and my mother cooked he cooked barbecue and she cooked corn on the cob and black eyed peas and everybody just had a wonderful time
Let's jump back a second.
When you learned that you'd been selected, how did you make your parents aware of that news?
You know, there was one phone in the guardroom of dorm two, and it was a pay phone.
My guess is I wrote them a letter.
I mean, frankly, I don't remember.
And to them, this was good, but they really didn't understand what it really meant.
And so I don't really remember.
Right.
So you went to summer camp.
Then did you go home or did you come back to A&M?
I came back early.
But I don't remember, I don't think I came right after summer camp.
And by the way, I had,
the spring of my junior year I had met my bride.
Typical Aggie courtship.

My roommate, again, was a fellow from Dallas and he and a lady named Kitty Hudnall, a Delta Gamma from North Texas, had been dating since high school, but it was one of these deals where it was on again, off again.
And I was always ending up having to be the father confessor and the cupid and trying to keep the thing going.
Well, Kitty was coming down one weekend, called Mac or sent a note or whatever and said, I've got a sorority friend on the rebound.
Anybody wants a date this weekend?
And that was the start.
And she was from a large metropolitan area also, wasn't she?
Marlin.
Yeah.
And had gone to North Texas, really following a future sister-in-law that she didn't know was going to be a sister-in-law at the time.
They had gone up there.
So this first date was a football weekend?
Basketball.
Played UT here.
Can still take you to the very seat that I sat in behind the
and it was because it was behind a girder, you know, old G. Raleigh White up in that northwest corner.
And we, I had my corps uniform on, of course, and I had a ribbon, and I can't remember what it was for, but it had stripes, and so she was,
We were in the back of a 65 Mustang driving around.
Mac has borrowed it from his mother and dad.
And she said, what's that ribbon?
And I said, well, I'm the core barber.
And she said, oh.
She didn't know what that meant, but it must have been important.
So we played this game for quite some time.
And then finally, she'd probably hate for me to reveal that she was that naive.
In those days, either use yourself or anyone else as an example, if you had a special date, where did you take that special date here in the College Station Bryan area?
There was nothing special.
there weren't any, number one, you didn't have any money, but number two, what little you had.
there wasn't a lot of places to go.
You had all of the following.
You had Zarapi's Mexican food, which was over near where, whatever that is now, Albertson's, I guess.
You had the Werman's, downtown Bryan, which was where we went to eat the first time my parents met my bride.
You had the chicken place,
I can't remember the name of it.
It went to South College.
Youngbloods.
Youngbloods.
The Texan in those days was the chicken fried drive-in place.
Ray Oldberger at the Circle.
There was a greasy spoon at Northgate.
But, I mean, you know, they were just another significant of a times and that sort of thing.
We're jumping around.
But there was a place at Northgate called Lou Ann's Restaurant.
A buddy of mine, our sophomore year, stayed down here for six weeks, went to school, and worked.
The only problem was we had to get by the first couple of weeks for the paycheck to come, and we didn't have anything to eat with.
And we went to Lou Ann's restaurant and made a deal with the owner that if he would give us a meal ticket just to get by two weeks.
